Here's my analysis of `OrderProcessorTests.cs`:

---

## Test Maintainability Report

**Summary:** 4 patterns found across 2 test classes (13 test methods total). The biggest win is the repeated `OrderProcessor` construction (8 identical blocks). The validator tests are also strong candidates for parameterization.

---

### Finding 1 — Repeated `OrderProcessor` Construction (8 occurrences) ⬆️ High

**Location:** Every test in `OrderProcessorTests` (lines 11–14, 34–37, 58–61, 82–85, 102–105, 125–128, 148–151, 170–173)

This 4-line block is copy-pasted in all 8 tests:
```csharp
var logger = new FakeLogger();
var emailService = new FakeEmailService();
var inventory = new FakeInventoryService(stockLevel: 100);
var processor = new OrderProcessor(logger, emailService, inventory);
```

**Suggested refactoring — `[TestInitialize]` + helper for non-default stock:**
```csharp
private FakeLogger _logger = null!;
private FakeEmailService _emailService = null!;
private OrderProcessor _processor = null!;

[TestInitialize]
public void Setup()
{
    _logger = new FakeLogger();
    _emailService = new FakeEmailService();
    _processor = CreateProcessor(stockLevel: 100);
}

private OrderProcessor CreateProcessor(int stockLevel)
    => new(new FakeLogger(), new FakeEmailService(),
           new FakeInventoryService(stockLevel));
```

The `OutOfStock` test (stock=0) can call `CreateProcessor(0)` directly. The other 7 tests just use `_processor`.

**Trade-off:** Tests lose some self-containment, but 7 of 8 use identical setup — the coupling is already implicit.

---

### Finding 2 — Copy-Paste Validator Failure Tests (4 occurrences) ⬆️ Medium

**Location:** `OrderValidatorTests` — `Validate_NullEmail_ReturnsFalse` (line 214), `Validate_EmptyItems_ReturnsFalse` (line 233), `Validate_NegativePrice_ReturnsFalse` (line 250), `Validate_ZeroQuantity_ReturnsFalse` (line 270)

All four follow the exact same structure — only the invalid property and expected error message change:
```csharp
var validator = new OrderValidator();
var order = new Order { /* one property differs */ };
var result = validator.Validate(order);
Assert.IsFalse(result.IsValid);
Assert.AreEqual("<error message>", result.ErrorMessage);
```

**Suggested refactoring — `[DynamicData]` parameterized test:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(InvalidOrderCases), DynamicDataSourceType.Method)]
public void Validate_InvalidOrder_ReturnsFalse(Order order, string expectedError)
{
    var validator = new OrderValidator();
    var result = validator.Validate(order);
    Assert.IsFalse(result.IsValid);
    Assert.AreEqual(expectedError, result.ErrorMessage);
}

private static IEnumerable<object[]> InvalidOrderCases()
{
    yield return new object[] {
        new Order { CustomerId = "C1", CustomerEmail = null!, Items = new() { /* valid item */ } },
        "Email is required" };
    yield return new object[] {
        new Order { CustomerId = "C2", CustomerEmail = "a@b.com", Items = new() },
        "Order must have items" };
    // ... etc.
}
```

`[DataRow]` isn't an option here since `Order` isn't a compile-time constant — `[DynamicData]` is the right fit.

**Trade-off:** Consolidates 4 methods → 1, but the data source method adds indirection. Test failure messages will need `DisplayName` to stay clear.

---

### Finding 3 — Repeated `Order` Construction (13 occurrences) ⬆️ Medium

**Location:** Every test in both classes.

Most tests build an `Order` with a single `OrderItem` using very similar boilerplate (~6 lines each):
```csharp
var order = new Order
{
    CustomerId = "C001",
    CustomerEmail = "alice@example.com",
    Items = new List<OrderItem>
    {
        new OrderItem { ProductId = "P1", Name = "Widget", Quantity = 2, UnitPrice = 9.99m }
    }
};
```

**Suggested refactoring — factory helper:**
```csharp
private static Order CreateOrder(
    string email = "test@example.com",
    bool isPremium = false,
    List<OrderItem>? items = null)
{
    items ??= new List<OrderItem>
    {
        new OrderItem { ProductId = "P1", Name = "Widget", Quantity = 1, UnitPrice = 9.99m }
    };
    return new Order { CustomerId = "C001", CustomerEmail = email,
                       IsPremium = isPremium, Items = items };
}
```

Tests then become: `var order = CreateOrder(email: null!)` or `CreateOrder(items: new())`.

**Trade-off:** Great readability improvement — each test highlights only what makes it unique. The factory hides defaults, so a new reader must check it once.

---

### Finding 4 — Processor Failure Tests (3 occurrences) 🔽 Low

**Location:** `ProcessOrder_EmptyItems_ReturnsFailed` (line 80), `ProcessOrder_NullEmail_ReturnsFailed` (line 99), `ProcessOrder_OutOfStock_ReturnsFailed` (line 122)

All three share the same shape: build processor → build invalid order → assert failure + status string. However, `OutOfStock` uses a different stock level, so they aren't pure clones. With Finding 1 + Finding 3 applied, these shrink to ~3 lines each, which is likely small enough to leave alone.

---

### Refactoring Priority

| Priority | Finding | Occurrences | Effort |
|----------|---------|-------------|--------|
| 1 | Processor construction → `[TestInitialize]` | 8 | Low |
| 2 | `Order` factory helper | 13 | Low |
| 3 | Validator failure → `[DynamicData]` | 4 | Medium |
| 4 | Processor failures (defer) | 3 | — |

Applying just #1 and #2 would eliminate roughly **60 lines** of repetition while keeping every test easy to read. The validator parameterization (#3) is optional — it's clean but adds indirection.
